// Recycling Importance Recycling Importance Click on the circles on each picture to learn more about why recycling is important Environmental Impact Economic Impact Why is it important to recycle properly? This is a picture of a sad recycling bin To ensure that the recycling process runs successfully, it is important to understand how it works and what can be recycled. One product that is recycled improperly can contaminate an entire bale of material (How to Recycle and Why You Should Do It, 2019). This contamination increase costs to ship the material to a landfill and damage equipment used in recycling (US EPA, 2017). Recycling Process Picture that shows environmental impact of recycling Recycling reduces the amount of waste in landfills, a big contributor of methane in the atmosphere. Recycling reduces the use of incineration. The incineration of landfill waste releases many greenhouse gases into the atmosphere, a big contributor to global warming. Recycling conserves natural resources which are in limited supply. Recycling conserves energy. It takes less energy to recycle materials than to produce products out of raw material since recyclable materials have already been processed. Picture that shows the economic impact of recycling Recycling allows for materials to be efficiently used to their full potential. The recycling cycle contributes to a sustainable circular economy. The recycling industry provides many jobs. In 2020, recycling provided 681,000 jobs and $37.8 billion in wages. Picture that shows the recycling process Firstly, the materials are collected by the town or a recycling facility Secondly, the materials are sorted, cleaned, and processed into usable manufacturing material. Thirdly, the processed materials are sold to manufacturing companies just like any raw material. Fourthly, the materials are manufactured into new products and the cycle continues.
