// Glass Information Page How to identify: • it is transparent or translucent • it is hard and brittle • A jar without the lid • Glass beverage bottles • Wine bottles but not wine glasses • Perfume bottles • Beer bottles • Olive oil bottle • Condiment bottles and jars • Clean the item of any solids or liquids // How to recycle glass • Do not recycle broken glass • Check that your glass is not treated with chemicals or covered in any type of coating. This kind of glass is not recyclable. • Check to see if glass is recyclable at your local recycling center • Some areas may require you to separate glass from other recyclable material • Put it in the recycling bin // Ideas how to reuse glass • Create a DIY project • Turn it into an instrument
// Metal Information Page Aluminum cans Examples of curbside recyclables: • Tin or aluminum cans • Disposable baking items • Aluminum foil • Paint cans Examples of NON curbside recyclables (must not infused with plastic): • Pots and pans • Metal utensils and other kitchen tools • Metal tools • Car parts or bicycle frames • Metal shelves and other metal furniture • Wire hangars • Metal is a hard, typically shiny material • It may be malleable and fusible • Clean the metal of any food or liquid residue • Metals under three inches like nails, screws, soda tabs, cannot be recycled and should be thrown away • If a substance is metallic but is infused with plastic (candy wrappers, cookie wrappers, metal juice pouches, etc.), it is not recyclable and must be thrown away. • Curbside recyclables can simply be thrown into a curbside recycling bin or brought to a recycling center. // how to recycle • Non-curbside recyclables can be donated or brought to a scrap yard, often with a light compensation • Electronics and appliances cannot be recycled but can be recycled at a Best Buy or Staples • Metal scraps can be remade into jewelery • Metal of varying size can be used to make art of varying size
// Paper Information Page Paper • Newspaper • Cup • Cardboard Box • Book • Printer Paper • Greeting Card • Egg Carton • Generally Easy to Bend • Pencil marks are easy to see on paper • Generally white or brown in color • Most town/city recycling facilities accept paper in their trucks • Grocery stores may accept paper bags • Large cardboard boxes can be thrown into large junk bins • Printer paper can be used for origami and crafts • Cardboard boxes can be used to package other items and ship them • Paper can be used for rough work and other homework assignments
