// Common Category Attributes Examples: How to Identify: How to Recycle: Ideas to Reuse: Return to Plastic Page
// Category1 Polyethylene Terephthalate • Soda/Water Bottles • Bean Bags • Plastic Jars • Clothes • Tough Material • Discolors when bent • Most, if not all, town/city recycling facilities accept this type of plastics in their trucks • Caps are generally removed prior to recycling • BPA free bottles can be reused to drink water • Bottles can be used for science experiments, such as the mentos and coke experiment • Homemade sauces and food items can be stored in used (and washed) plastic containers
// Category2 High-Density Polyethylene • Milk Bottles • Bleach and Detergent Bottles • Bottle Caps • Soap Bottles • Tough and Rigid Material • Springs back to original shape when bent • Most, if not all, town/city recycling facilities accept this type of plastics in their trucks • Caps are generally removed prior to recycling • Foods could be stored in bottles, as long as they are properly washed • Soaps, shampoo, and other liquids of that type can be stored in these plastics until use • It is important to be mindful of the estrogen-mimicking additive chemicals that may be present
// Category3 Polyvinyl Chloride • Toys • Food Trays • Pipes • Wire Insulation • Fragile and easy to bend (creases form when bent) • Make a cracking sound when bent (bottles especially) • Most recycling facilities do not accept this type of plastic • It is important to monitor local regulations regarding recycling • PVC pipes can be implemented in a variety of ways since they do not rust like many metals • It is a pretty hazardous plastic so, while it can be used, it is essential to be careful
// Category4 Low-Density Polyethylene • Plastic Grocery Bags • Frozen Food Bags • Trash Bags • Wraps and Coatings • Low density and weight • Flexible and easy to tear • Most recycling facilities do not accept this type of plastic • Grocery stores may accept plastic bags to redistribute • Plastic bags make a good parachute in egg drop experiments • Bags are hard to breathe in, so caution is required
// Category5 Polypropylene • Soup Containers • Tubs for Butter or Margarine • Bottle Caps • Glass Jar Caps • Quite durable and sometimes hard to break • Will shatter if broken • Most recycling facilities do not accept this type of plastic • More effective to reuse • Used containers can be used to store foods • Thermoses and reusable bottles often use Polypropylene because of its heat resistance
// Category6 Polystyrene • Packing Peanuts • Food Containers and To-Go Boxes • Disposable Cups • Trays and Plates (Styrofoam Products) • Rigid but easy to break • Easy to tear or pull apart • Styrofoam should not be recycled • Reusing is also difficult • Can be used to pack items in a parcel to ship • It is hazardous (should be kept away from children) and is hard to reuse
// Category 7 Other Plastics • Polycarbonate • Reading Glasses • CDs and DVDs • Some wires • Hard material and likely to shatter • Often found in materials that require special disposal • Polycarbonate and other plastics should not be recycled • If not reused, these plastics should be thrown uun the trash • Some CDs allow a user to wipe the existing data and insert new data • Polycarbonate is especially dangerous due to its cancerous properties and its use has been widely discontinued
